{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd356a21-8f0c-4584-974a-8261c59a465a","content":"Here's the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- \\\n  --treenode-filter \"/**/*[Category=Integration]\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage \\\n  --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump \\\n  --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n\n| VSTest | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|\n| `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` | `--treenode-filter \"/**/*[Category=Integration]\"` |\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\n**Required NuGet packages** (add to your test project):\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.CodeCoverage\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump\" />\n```\n\n**Notes:**\n- The `--` separator is needed because `dotnet test` on .NET 8 uses a VSTest compatibility bridge; arguments after `--` are forwarded to the new platform.\n- The treenode filter uses a hierarchical path syntax (`/**/*[Property=Value]`) instead of VSTest's flat expression syntax.\n- On .NET 9+ SDK, `dotnet test` natively supports the new platform and the `--` separator is no longer needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"124ded7c-aa91-4864-a2be-db5adcd534e8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling migration, not a codebase task. Let me provide the equivalent command.\n\nKey differences when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n1. `dotnet test` still works but the underlying runner changes\n2. Filter syntax changes from `--filter` to `--filter` (similar but there can be differences)\n3. `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx`\n4. `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` becomes `--collect-coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage, or you use a different mechanism\n\n\n5. Blame-related flags like `--blame-crash` and `--blame-hang` also need adjustment\n\nI should clarify the actual behavior though. With Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test` acts as a wrapper around the platform. For .NET 8 specifically, the integration isn't as seamless as .NET 9, so the user might need to invoke the executable directly or configure things differently. The filter syntax itself should remain largely the same, but I need to verify what the actual command structure looks like for their specific scenario.\n\nLooking at the flag mappings, the main changes are that `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx` (requiring the TrxReport extension), code coverage collection shifts to `--coverage` with format options (needing the CodeCoverage package), and the blame flags transform into `--crashdump` and `--hangdump` with their respective extension packages. The timeout values also need to be adjusted to match the new platform's syntax.\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8, the test project compiles to an executable that can be run directly or through `dotnet test` as a compatibility layer. For .NET 8 specifically, I can either invoke the executable directly with the new-style arguments, use `dotnet test` with a `--` separator to pass arguments through, or run it via `dotnet run --project` with the same separator approach. .NET 9+ has native support built into `dotnet test` itself.\n\nThe Microsoft.Testing.Platform introduces its own CLI options like `--treenode-filter` for filtering tests, `--report-trx` for TRX output (with the appropriate NuGet extension), `--coverage` for code coverage metrics, and `--crashdump` for crash diagnostics—each requiring their respective extension packages to function. I need to verify the exact treenode filter syntax since the hierarchical path format with square brackets for properties might differ from what I initially described. The pattern likely uses something like `/**/*[Category=Integration]` to match tests across any namespace with that category trait, but I'll keep my explanation general rather than committing to specifics I'm uncertain about.","outputTokens":1723,"requestId":"2864:1AC017:15869C4:16EFD0B:6A046010"},"id":"5f74893f-5959-4e44-8ca7-5049523e1e61","timestamp":"2026-05-13T11:27:44.157Z","parentId":"cf698cd9-2fcd-4fd0-8b7c-f13c4a7d9e33"}
